I think the bread in the vacuum jar in the oven must have started cooking before the seal failed, because if it was just raw dough when the air got into the jar I think it would have collapsed instead of staying nice and fluffy.

Since vacuum doesn't conduct heat, the dough didn't even start cooking until the jar got hot enough to start cooking the dough where it was in direct contact, which means that it started cooking at the very bottom where it was in direct contact with the hot glass. This is unusual; normally the top and sides of the rolls are directly exposed to the heat of the oven, while the bottom is shielded by a baking sheet (which starts at room temperature). I think that's why the bottom of the roll was crispy.

So at this point you might expect the bottom to burn while the top remained completely raw. But the dough cooking would also create some gases, so the jar would have gradually started to repressurize from the gases produced by the cooking dough. As the gases from the dough started to repressurize the jar, that would have allowed heat to transfer through to start cooking the rest of the dough. The result was a perfectly cooked roll that was crispy all around.

The rubber seal on the lid was a wild card. It had the potential to result in a flat hockey puck if that seal failed too early and the jar repressurized suddenly (which honestly was what I was expecting). By the time the lid's rubber seal failed, I think that either the dough had already set up into its cooked shape well enough, or it had generated enough of an atmosphere that the change in pressure wasn't drastic enough, or probably a combination of both, so that it didn't collapse when the rubber seal failed like the raw one did when its jar was repressurized.

Biscuit dough vs bread dough -
The varying results you see are mostly due to gluten differences within the dough. Biscuits are a ‘short’ dough as in the gluten is intentionally underdeveloped. The short strands of protein create a tender and melt in your mouth biscuit. In bread roll dough, the gluten is intentionally developed and needs to rest to relax it. This gives the dough a stretchy glutinous structure that creates a slightly chewy bread that has even air pockets throughout. That’s why they react so differently in the vacuum chamber. Developed gluten doughs will always grow much more than short doughs.
